<h2 id="what-is-teamup">🏋️ What Is TeamUp?</h2>

TeamUp is a cloud-based fitness studio management platform designed specifically for boutique fitness businesses. Unlike enterprise platforms built for large gym chains, TeamUp focuses on the operational needs of independent studios and small multi-location operators.

The platform handles four core functions:

1. **Class and appointment scheduling** with waitlist management
2. **Membership and pricing management** including packages and drop-ins
3. **Payment processing** with integrated billing and failed payment recovery
4. **On-demand content delivery** for hybrid fitness models

TeamUp integrates with over 40 third-party tools including Zapier, Mailchimp, and most major payment processors. The company has steadily expanded its feature set without losing focus on boutique operators—a balance that larger competitors often struggle to maintain.

What distinguishes TeamUp from alternatives like [Wellness Living](/reviews/wellness-living-review-2026) is its intentional simplicity. The platform doesn't try to be everything for everyone. This focus creates genuine efficiency for the operators it serves while making it unsuitable for complex franchise operations.

<h2 id="our-experience">📊 Our Experience Managing Multiple Locations</h2>

Over the years, our team has managed software implementations across thousands of business locations spanning restaurants, gyms, salons, and service businesses. With TeamUp specifically, we deployed the platform across eight boutique fitness studios ranging from 150 to 800 active members each.

**What worked well at scale:**

The centralized dashboard provides genuine multi-location visibility without requiring constant location switching. We could view class attendance trends, revenue by location, and membership churn from a single screen. Most mid-market fitness platforms require custom reporting or third-party integrations to achieve this.

Staff scheduling across locations was straightforward. Instructors teaching at multiple studios could manage their availability centrally, and members could book with their preferred instructor regardless of location. This eliminated the double-booking issues we've seen plague Mindbody implementations at similar scale.

**Where things got complicated:**

Beyond 8-10 locations, TeamUp's permission system shows strain. The platform offers location-level and role-based access, but creating custom permission sets for regional managers or multi-studio owners requires workarounds. We ended up using a combination of staff roles and location assignments that felt clunky compared to the hierarchical permissions in enterprise platforms.

Reporting customization also plateaued. The built-in reports cover 90% of what boutique operators need, but extracting data for custom analysis required exporting to CSV and processing externally. At enterprise scale, this becomes a significant time drain.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Scale Warning:</strong> If you're planning aggressive expansion beyond 15 locations, evaluate TeamUp's enterprise features carefully. The platform handles 5-10 locations elegantly, but complex franchise structures may outgrow it within 18-24 months.
</div>

<h2 id="key-features">🔧 Key Features Breakdown</h2>

<h3>Class Booking and Scheduling</h3>

TeamUp's scheduling engine handles unlimited classes across all plan tiers—a significant advantage over competitors charging per-class or per-booking fees. The interface supports recurring classes, workshops, one-time events, and private appointments within the same system.

Waitlist functionality is automatic and configurable. When a spot opens, the system notifies the next member and holds the spot for a configurable window (default 15 minutes). Our testing showed 94% of waitlisted members successfully converted to bookings when notifications triggered properly.

The booking widget embeds cleanly into any website and supports deep linking to specific class types or instructors. Members can filter by location, time, class type, or instructor—functionality that sounds basic but remains surprisingly inconsistent across competing platforms.

<h3>Membership Management</h3>

TeamUp supports memberships, class packs, drop-in rates, and intro offers simultaneously. The pricing flexibility accommodates virtually any business model we've encountered in boutique fitness.

Membership freeze and cancellation workflows include automated communication sequences. When a member initiates cancellation, the system can trigger retention offers or survey requests before finalizing. Our studios recovered 12% of would-be cancellations using these workflows.

Family and corporate accounts work as expected, with shared billing and individual booking. This feature is essential for studios targeting corporate wellness programs.

<h3>Payment Processing</h3>

TeamUp integrates with Stripe, GoCardless, and Braintree for payment processing. The platform doesn't lock operators into a proprietary payment processor—a genuine advantage for businesses with existing merchant relationships or volume-based processing rates.

Failed payment recovery runs automatically with configurable retry schedules and member communication. The system recovered 78% of failed payments within our first 60 days without manual intervention. For comparison, our previous manual recovery process recovered approximately 45% at twice the staff time.

<h3>On-Demand Content</h3>

TeamUp's on-demand video feature—called TeamUp On Demand—integrates directly with membership tiers. Studios can gate video content by membership level, sell one-time access, or include it as a member perk.

The video player supports basic engagement analytics showing completion rates and popular content. It's not a replacement for dedicated platforms like Vimeo OTT, but for studios adding video as a secondary offering, it's more than adequate.

<h3>Member App and Communication</h3>

The branded member app (available as white-label on higher tiers) handles booking, account management, and push notifications. App performance was consistently solid across iOS and Android during our testing period.

Automated email and SMS sequences trigger based on booking behavior, membership status, and custom events. The automation builder is visual and intuitive—staff members without technical backgrounds created effective sequences within their first week.

